# Dev server policy

**Do not** start dev servers or long-running watch processes unless the user explicitly asks (e.g. “run dev”, “verify in the browser”). If they do, use the project’s **`bun run dev`** from the repo root and stop or ask before leaving a server running forever.

## What not to run without an explicit user request

- `bun dev`, `npm run dev`, `yarn dev`
- `npm start`, `yarn start`
- Watch commands (`--watch`, `nodemon`, etc.)
- Any long-running development processes

## What is okay to run

- Build commands: `bun run build`, `npm run build`
- Type checking: `bun run typecheck` (repo root; packages use `tsgo --noEmit`)
- Linting: `bun run lint` or `biome check` (Biome only in this repo)
- Tests: `bun test`, `npm test`
- Database migrations: `bun run db:migrate`
- Code generation: `bun run db:generate`, `typegen`
- One-off scripts and utilities

## When dev server is needed but was not explicitly requested

Instead of running the dev server, tell the user:

```
You'll need to restart your dev server to see these changes:

bun dev
```

Or if they need to test in the browser:

```
Test the changes using the URL from the dev terminal (`Local:` line — often port 5173, else the next free port)
```

## Why

- Dev servers run indefinitely and consume resources
- User may already have a dev server running
- User prefers to control when processes start/stop
